=== Sixth proof ===

This proof is based on the Dyck words interpretation of the Catalan numbers and uses the cycle lemma of Dvoretzky and Motzkin.

We call a sequence of X&#x27;s and Y&#x27;s &quot;dominating&quot; if, reading from left to right, the number of X&#x27;s is always strictly greater than the number of Y&#x27;s. The cycle lemma states that any sequence of formula_65 X&#x27;s and formula_66 Y&#x27;s, where formula_67, has precisely formula_68 dominating circular shifts. To see this, arrange the given sequence of formula_69 X&#x27;s and Y&#x27;s in a circle. Repeatedly removing XY pairs leaves exactly formula_68 X&#x27;s. Each of these X&#x27;s was the start of a dominating circular shift before anything was removed. For example, consider formula_71. This sequence is dominating, but none of its circular shifts formula_72, formula_73, formula_74 and formula_75 are.

A string is a Dyck word of formula_66 X&#x27;s and formula_66 Y&#x27;s if and only if prepending an X to the Dyck word gives a dominating sequence with formula_78 X&#x27;s and formula_66 Y&#x27;s, so we can count the former by instead counting the latter. In particular, when formula_80, there is exactly one dominating circular shift. There are formula_81 sequences with exactly formula_78 X&#x27;s and formula_66 Y&#x27;s. For each of these, only one of the formula_84 circular shifts is dominating. Therefore there are formula_85 distinct sequences of formula_78 X&#x27;s and formula_66 Y&#x27;s that are dominating, each of which corresponds to exactly one Dyck word.

== Hankel matrix ==

The Hankel matrix whose entry is the Catalan number has determinant 1, regardless of the value of . For example, for we have
:formula_88

Moreover, if the indexing is &quot;shifted&quot; so that the entry is filled with the Catalan number then the determinant is still 1, regardless of the value of .
For example, for we have
:formula_89

Taken together, these two conditions uniquely define the Catalan numbers.

Another feature unique to the Catalan–Hankel matrix is that the submatrix starting at has determinant .

:formula_90

:formula_91

:formula_92

:formula_93

et cetera.

== History ==

The Catalan sequence was described in 1751 by Leonhard Euler, who was interested in the number of different ways of dividing a polygon into triangles. The sequence is named after Eugène Charles Catalan, who discovered the connection to parenthesized expressions during his exploration of the Towers of Hanoi puzzle. The reflection counting trick (second proof) for Dyck words was found by Désiré André in 1887.

The name “Catalan numbers” originated from John Riordan.

In 1988, it came to light that the Catalan number sequence had been used in China by the Mongolian mathematician Mingantu by 1730. That is when he started to write his book &quot;Ge Yuan Mi Lu Jie Fa&quot; &quot;[The Quick Method for Obtaining the Precise Ratio of Division of a Circle]&quot;, which was completed by his student Chen Jixin in 1774 but published sixty years later. Peter J. Larcombe (1999) sketched some of the features of the work of Mingantu, including the stimulus of Pierre Jartoux, who brought three infinite series to China early in the 1700s.

For instance, Ming used the Catalan sequence to express series expansions of formula_94 and formula_95 in terms of formula_96.

== Generalizations ==
The Catalan numbers can be interpreted as a special case of the Bertrand&#x27;s ballot theorem. Specifically, formula_15 is the number of ways for a candidate A with votes to lead candidate B with votes.

The two-parameter sequence of non-negative integers formula_98
is a generalization of the Catalan numbers. These are named super-Catalan numbers, per Ira Gessel. These should not confused with the Schröder–Hipparchus numbers, which sometimes are also called super-Catalan numbers.

For formula_99, this is just two times the ordinary Catalan numbers, and for formula_100, the numbers have an easy combinatorial description.
However, other combinatorial descriptions are only known
for formula_101 and formula_102,
and it is an open problem to find a general combinatorial interpretation.

Sergey Fomin and Nathan Reading have given a generalized Catalan number associated to any finite crystallographic Coxeter group, namely the number of fully commutative elements of the group; in terms of the associated root system, it is the number of anti-chains (or order ideals) in the poset of positive roots. The classical Catalan number formula_15 corresponds to the root system of type formula_104. The classical recurrence relation generalizes: the Catalan number of a Coxeter diagram is equal to the sum of the Catalan numbers of all its maximal proper sub-diagrams.

The Catalan numbers are a solution of a version of the Hausdorff moment problem.

